The paper introduces a novel type theory and logic for probabilistic reasoning, which falls under the category of mathematical logic. Therefore, cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the computation rules for calculating conditional probabilities, which involves artificial intelligence techniques, making cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) another likely sub-category. The paper also deals with graphical models, which are commonly used in machine learning, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) another possible sub-category. The paper also discusses the specification and verification of programs, which falls under the category of programming languages, making cs.PL (Programming Languages) another possible sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the normalisation and conditioning of states, which involves information theory, making cs.IT (Information Theory) another possible sub-category.
